 (1) GAO Recommends Greater Collaboration Among Charitable
         Organizations in Future Disasters

 A new report from the General Accounting Office
 ( http://www.gao.gov/ ), the investigative arm of Congress,
 recommends that the Federal Emergency Management Agency
 ( http://www.fema.gov/ ) begin working with major charities
 to improve the way contributions intended to help victims
 of large-scale disasters like the September 11 terrorist
 attacks are collected and distributed, the Associated Press
 reports.

 According to the GAO report, a lack of coordination among
 charities in the days after the September 11 attacks led
 to confusion among aid recipients, many of whom were
 bewildered by the maze of service providers and intimated
 by the attendant paperwork and bureaucracy. The report
 adds that the situation improved over several months, as
 large charities and relief agencies worked together to
 coordinate their activities and client databases.

 "Charities can learn many lessons from the events of
 September 11th," said Sen. Charles E. Grassley (R-IA), who
 requested the report. "By working together to pool infor-
 mation and resources, I believe charities can do an even
 better job at helping those in need."

 "GAO Reports on 9/11 Charities." Washington Post 1/03/03.

 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=20800021

 -------------------------<<>>--------------------------

 (2) Kaiser Family Foundation Collaborates with Viacom to
         Launch Campaign Against HIV/AIDS

 The Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation
 ( http://www.kff.org/ ) in Menlo Park, California, and
 media giant Viacom Inc. ( http://www.viacom.com/ ) have
 launched a new media campaign to combat HIV/AIDS with
 public service announcements, television and radio
 programming, and free print and online content about
 the disease and its prevention.

 The KNOW HIV/AIDS ( http://www.knowhivaids.org/ ) campaign
 will combine the public health knowledge of the Kaiser
 Family Foundation and the broad reach of Viacom's media
 brands to educate the general population about the impact
 of AIDS globally and to promote prevention and testing
 among higher-risk populations, including young people
 under the age of twenty-five, people of color, women,
 and men who have sex with men. Several creative agencies
 have developed the campaign's twenty-two television spots,
 fourteen radio ads, and thirteen outdoor ads, all of which
 will be offered rights-free to other media and inter-
 national broadcasters. In 2003, the campaign will place
 ads worth about $120 million on Viacom's broadcast networks,
 CBS and UPN, and on several of the company's cable networks,
 including MTV, VH1, and Nickelodeon.

 "Viacom's brands are cultural trendsetters like no other,
 with strong and loyal ties to the people we're trying to
 reach," said Viacom president and COO Mel Karmazin. "Our
 mission is to inform people and compel them to act -- to
 protect themselves, and get tested for the virus. We hope
 other media companies around the world will join us in
 fighting this epidemic with the most powerful communica-
 tions tools that exist -- their television, radio, outdoor,
 newspaper, magazine, and online assets."

 In addition to support from Viacom and the Kaiser Family
 Foundation, the campaign has received funding from the
 Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation
 ( http://www.gatesfoundation.org/ ), the Mel Karmazin
 Foundation, and Viacom chairman and CEO Sumner Redstone.

 "Viacom and Kaiser Family Foundation Launch Comprehensive
 Initiative to Fight HIV/AIDS." Henry J. Kaiser Family
 Foundation Press Release 01/06/03.
 http://www.kff.org/content/2003/20030106a/Viacom_Press_Release.pdf

 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=21000016

 -------------------------<<>>--------------------------

 (3) Ford Foundation Announces New International Fellows

 The Ford Foundation International Fellowships Program
 ( http://www.fordifp.net/ ) has announced the selection
 of 407 new fellows from developing countries to receive
 support for up to three years of graduate study in a
 university program.

 Selected from a pool of more than 10,000 applicants from
 twenty-two countries and territories, the winners were
 chosen based on their academic achievement, commitment
 to the development of their communities and countries,
 and strong leadership skills and potential. The program,
 which was launched in 2000 with a $280 million grant from
 the Ford Foundation ( http://www.fordfound.org/ ), has
 named a total of 691 fellows since June 2001 and plans
 to select some 3,000 by 2010. The most recent group
 includes fellows chosen for the first time from the
 countries of Brazil, Egypt, Indonesia, Mozambique,
 Palestine, the Philippines, and South Africa.

 "These IFP fellows represent a new generation of leaders
 whose perspectives rise from diverse communities and
 grassroots realities," said Ford Foundation president
 Susan V. Berresford. "The fellows are linked by their
 commitment to apply their further education to promoting
 human development and social justice in their communities
 and countries."

 The program, an initiative of the International Fellow-
 ships Fund, an independent supporting organization of
 the Institute of International Education
 ( http://www.iie.org/ ), works closely with local
 committees formed by IFP international partner organ-
 izations and Ford Foundation officials in Africa, Asia,
 Latin America, the Middle East, and Russia to choose
 fellows from groups and communities that lack systematic
 access to higher education.

 "Ford Foundation International Fellowships Program Names
 407 New Winners." Ford Foundation Press Release 1/07/03.

 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=21000005

 Related News:
 Ford Foundation International Fellowships Program
     Announces Second Round of Fellows (02/21/02)
 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=5400036

