 (4) Large Donations in Silicon Valley Shift from Stock
         to Cash

 During the economic boom of the 1990s, charities in
 Silicon Valley frequently received charitable gifts of
 stock. But with the collapse in stock prices that began
 in the spring of 2000, donors have all but stopped giving
 equities and are donating cash instead, the San Jose
 Mercury News reports.

 "All we are getting is cash," said Karen Bradley-Follette,
 vice president of development and marketing at the
 San Jose-based Community Foundation Silicon Valley
 ( http://www.cfsv.org/ ). According to Bradley-Follette,
 at least 90 percent of the donations received by CFSV in
 2000 came in the form of stock -- a ratio that lately is
 almost reversed. Donors tend to favor gifts of stock when
 share prices are high because they receive a charitable
 deduction based on the sale price of the stock, as opposed
 to its purchase price. Conversely, when the price drops,
 it reduces the value of the stock as a tax-deductible gift.

 But gifts of stock haven't completely dried up, says
 Ash McNeely, vice president of philanthropic services
 at the Peninsula Community Foundation ( http://www.pcf.org/ )
 in San Mateo. "Before, we'd see primarily tech stocks,
 IPO-related stock. Now we are seeing consumer product
 stocks, utility stocks, classic blue chip stocks."

 And while the foundation has seen its donations drop from
 $230 million in 2000 to $99 million in 2001 to $57 million
 in 2002, it has managed to award about $63 million to
 nonprofits in each of the last three years.

 Boudreau, John. "Cash Replaces Stock Gifts Among Wealthy
 Donors." San Jose Mercury News 1/01/03.
 http://www.bayarea.com/mld/mercurynews/news/local/4853211.htm

 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=20800023

