 (6) Arts Center Receives $1 Million and Drops Donors'
         Names

 In conjunction with the announcement of a new $1 million
 donation to a Palm Beach, Florida-based visual arts center
 named their honor, Robert and Mary Montgomery have asked
 the center to revert to its original name, the Armory Arts
 Center ( http://www.armoryarts.org/ ), in the hope that
 the name change will help the center attract larger con-
 tributions, the Palm Beach Daily News reports.

 The nonprofit center, which has received more than
 $2.8 million from the Montgomerys since it was founded
 in 1987, was re-named the Robert & Mary Montgomery Armory
 Art Center in 1997. The center will continue to honor the
 Montgomerys by adding their names to an historic 1939
 classroom building on campus.

 "In our discussions with Bob and Mary, we've talked about
 our not being able to attract large donations," said Jane
 McGregor, chair of the Armory board. "The feeling is that
 having [their] names attached to the campus is a detriment
 to getting larger donations, because there wasn't a strong
 naming opportunity and some people perceived that the
 Montgomerys owned the Armory. By taking their names off,
 we leave opportunities open for larger donors."

 Sjostrom, Jan. "Armory to Lose Patrons' Names." Palm Beach
 Daily News 1/28/03.

http://www.gopbi.com/auto/pbdn/feed/news/2002/12/28/1041053949.01917.4783.18
24.html

 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=20900015

 -------------------------<<>>--------------------------

 (7) Helen Bader Foundation Announces Grants Totaling
         $6.3 Million

 The Helen Bader Foundation ( http://www.hbf.org/ ) in
 Milwaukee, Wisconsin, has awarded ninety new grants
 totaling nearly $6.3 million for programs in the United
 States and Israel that focus on Alzheimer's disease and
 dementia, early childhood and youth development,
 education, economic and community development, and
 Jewish life and learning.

 The largest grant in this round of funding was a three-
 year, $1.2 million grant to the Helen Bader Scholarship
 Fund at the Milwaukee Jewish Federation
 ( http://www.milwaukeejewish.org/ ) to provide tuition
 assistance to students attending the five Jewish day
 schools in the Milwaukee area. The contribution marks a
 20 percent increase in the foundation's support to the
 Fund, which has provided more than $3.7 million in
 scholarships since 1991.

 "Many families believe Jewish day schools reinforce
 their values, but they may be daunted by the cost of
 tuition," said Tobey Libber, the foundation's Jewish
 Life and Learning program officer. "The Fund is intended
 to keep the day schools within reach of the greatest
 number of families."

 "Helen Bader Foundation Awards $6.2 Million in New
 Grants." Helen Bader Foundation Press Release 12/20/02.
 http://www.hbf.org/news/news_02_Dec20.html

 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=20900009

 -------------------------<<>>--------------------------

 (8) Saint Paul Foundation Announces $5.25 Million
         in Grants

 The Saint Paul Foundation
 ( http://www.saintpaulfoundation.org/ ), which serves the
 greater St. Paul, Minnesota area, has announced 865 grants
 totaling $5.25 million, including thirty-seven grants
 with a combined value of $2.6 million from the foundation's
 unrestricted funds.

 Grants made by the foundation include awards of $250,000
 each to Twin Cities Public Television Inc.
 ( http://www.ktca.org/ ) to help fund the station's tran-
 sition to digital programming; the United Jewish Fund
 and Council ( http://www.jewishminnesota.org/ ), which
 works to unite, sustain, and enhance the Jewish community
 in St. Paul; and the Young Women's Christian Association
 of St. Paul ( http://www.ywcaofstpaul.org/ ).

 In addition, the foundation awarded $200,000 to the
 Guadalupe Alternative Programs ( http://www.gapschool.org/ ),
 a nonprofit organization that operates alternative high
 schools and provides adult education in St. Paul; $150,000
 to the Center for Victims of Torture ( http://www.cvt.org/ ),
 which offers treatment for torture survivors and their
 families; and $100,000 to the Community Reinvestment Fund
 ( http://www.crfusa.com/ ) for a small business expansion
 program in the city.

 "The Saint Paul Foundation Approves 865 Grants Totaling
 $5.2 Million." Saint Paul Foundation Press Release 12/17/02.
 http://www.saintpaulfoundation.org/news/press/index.asp?sid=29&id=380&p=1

 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=20900011

 -------------------------<<>>--------------------------

 (9) Spelman College Receives $2 Million from Lilly
         Endowment

 Spelman College ( http://www.spelman.edu/ ) in Atlanta
 has been selected as one of the thirty-nine colleges to
 receive funding from the Indianapolis-based Lilly
 Endowment to implement programs focused on religion and
 spirituality. The school, which was awarded a five-year,
 $2 million grant, is one of two historically black schools
 and one of two women's colleges to receive an award in
 this round of grantmaking.

 Spelman's new program, Sisters Center for WISDOM: Women
 in Spiritual Discernment of Ministry, aims to increase
 student, faculty, and staff awareness of and knowledge
 about religious vocations, spirituality, and ethical
 leadership; recruit and retain students pursuing the
 ministry as a vocation; expand the college's related
 course offerings; and establish connections with religious
 groups in the community. The program also is designed to
 increase research and scholarship on black women, religion,
 and spirituality and examine the gender-based disparities
 and inequities that have affected society and the church
 in the past.

 "Although women represent 75 percent of church membership,
 they are disproportionately represented in senior
 positions in the Black church," said Rev. Lisa Rhodes, a
 dean at the college. "The grant will enable us to develop
 programs that help students explore career choice and
 vocation as a calling, and religious leadership and
 pastoral ministry as a viable vocational option."

 "Lilly Endowment Awards Spelman College $2 Million to
 Establish Sisters Center for WISDOM: Women in Spiritual
 Discernment of Ministry." Spelman College Press Release
 12/13/02.

 http://fdncenter.org/pnd/news/story.jhtml?id=20700024

